{"title":"Learning to Compose Task-Specific Tree Structures","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Recursive neural networks for sentence encoding typically require supervised parse trees, which are costly to obtain and may not align with the optimal structure for a given downstream task. The challenge is to learn task-specific, discrete tree compositions directly from plain text while remaining trainable end-to-end.","method":"Introduce Gumbel Tree-LSTM, a bottom-up Tree-LSTM that repeatedly composes adjacent nodes into parent candidates and selects one parent per layer until a single sentence vector remains. A trainable composition query vector scores each candidate (via q·h), and Straight-Through Gumbel-Softmax is used to sample a discrete parent during training (argmax at test), enabling standard backpropagation through the otherwise discrete selection. The layer-wise construction supports efficient batched computation without explicit parse inputs."},{"problem":"Composing trees from plain text using only local word representations can yield suboptimal merge decisions because leaves lack broader sentence context.","method":"Augment the model with an LSTM-based leaf transformation that runs over the input words to provide each leaf node with sequential context before any tree composition. This hybridizes sequential context with tree-structured composition (without a parser/tracking LSTM), improving parent selection and yielding substantial performance and convergence gains in experiments."}]}
